untry's credit rating |date=15 April 2011 |first1=Simon |last1=Rogers |first2=Ami |last2=Sedghi |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2010/apr/30/credit-ratings-country-fitch-moodys-standard |accessdate=31 May 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\n*A+ (Domestic)\n*A+ (Foreign)\n*AA+ (T&C Assessment)\n*Outlook: Stable\n*[[Moody's]]:<ref name=guardian/>\n*A1\n*Outlook: Stable\n*[[Fitch Group|Fitch]]:<ref name=guardian/>\n*A\n*Outlook: Stable\n*Scope:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scoperatings.com/#search/research/detail/160042EN|title=Scope affirms Japan's credit rating at A+ with a Stable Outlook|author=Scope Ratings|date=21 June 2019|website=Scope Ratings|accessdate=24 June 2019}}</ref>\n*A+\n*Outlook: Stable}}\n|aid                 = ''donor'': [[Official development assistance|ODA]], $10.37 billion (2016)<ref name=\"oecd-aid\">{{cite web|title=Development aid rises again in 2016 but flows to poorest countries dip |url=http://www.oecd.org/dac/development-aid-rises-again-in-2016-but-flows-to-poorest-countries-dip.htm |website=[[OECD]] |accessdate=25 September 2017 |date=11 April 2017 }}</ref>  \n|cianame             = ja\n|spelling            = US\n}} \nThe '''economy of Japan''' is a [[Developed country|highly developed]] free-[[market economy]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Lechevalier |first=S\u00e9bastien |date=2014 |title=The Great Transformation of Japanese Capitalism|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=s3vMAgAAQBAJ&dq=japan+economy+and+capitalism&source=gbs_navlinks_s |location= |publisher=[[Routledge]] |page=204 |isbn=9781317974963}}</ref> It is the [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|third-largest]] in the world by [[gross domestic product|nominal GDP]] and the [[List of countries by GDP (PPP)|fourth-largest]] by [[purchasing power parity]] (PPP).<ref name = imf2>{{cite web|title=World Economic Outlook Database, April 2016 \u2013 Report for Selected Countries and Subjects|url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2016/01/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=51&pr.y=3&sy=2016&ey=2020&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=158&s=NGDPD%2CNGDPDPC%2CPPPGDP%2CPPPPC&grp=0&a=|publisher=[[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF)|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Economy slips to third in world\">{{cite news | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/BUSINESS/02/13/japan.economy.third/index.html | title=Japan: Economy slips to third in world | work=[[CNN]].com | date=14 February 2011 | agency=CNN | author=Kyung Lah}}</ref> and is the world's second largest [[developed economy]].<ref name=\"OECD\">{{cite news | url=http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/economics/country-statistical-profile-japan_20752288-table-jpn | title=Country statistical profile: Japan | work=[[OECD iLibrary]] | date=28 February 2013 | accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> [[Japan]] is a member of the [[G7 (major advanced economies)|G7]]. According to the [[International Monetary Fund]], the country's [[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita|per capita GDP]] (PPP) was at $38,937 (2016).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Japan: 2017 Article IV Consultation : Press Release ; Staff Report ; and Statement by the Executive Director for Japan.|date=2017|publisher=International Monetary Fund|others=International Monetary Fund. Asia and Pacific Department|isbn=9781484313497|location=Washington, D.C.|oclc=1009601181}}</ref> Due to a volatile currency exchange rate, Japan's GDP as measured in dollars fluctuates sharply. Accounting for these fluctuations through the use of the [[Atlas method]], Japan is estimated to have a GDP per capita of around $38,490. The Japanese economy is forecast by the [[Tankan|Quarterly Tankan survey of business sentiment]] conducted by the [[Bank of Japan]].<ref name=\"Bank of Japan\">{{cite web | url=http://www.boj.or.jp/en/statistics/tk/index.htm/ | title=TANKAN \uff1a\u65e5\u672c\u9280\u884c Bank of Japan | publisher=Boj.or.jp | work=[[Bank of Japan]] | accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> The [[Nikkei 225]] presents the monthly report of top [[Blue chip (stock market)|blue chip]] equities on [[Japan Exchange Group]], which is the world's [[List of stock exchanges|third-largest stock exchange]] by [[market capitalisation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.world-exchanges.org/our-work/statistics|title=Monthly Reports - World Federation of Exchanges|publisher=WFE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://indexes.nikkei.co.jp/en/nkave/newsroom |title= Nikkei Indexes |website= indexes.nikkei.co.jp}}</ref> In 2018, Japan was the world's [[List of countries by imports|fourth-largest importer]] and the [[List of countries by exports|fourth-largest exporter]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wto.org/english/res_e/statis_e/wts2019_e/wts2019_e.pdf |title=World Trade Statistical Review 2019 |work=[[World Trade Organization]] |page=100 |accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref> It has the world's [[List of countries by foreign-exchange reserves|second-largest]] foreign-exchange reserves worth $1.3 trillion.<ref name=\"Japan_reserves\"/> It ranks 29th on [[Ease of doing business index]] and 5th on [[Global Competitiveness Report]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reports.weforum.org/global-competitiveness-report-2018/|title=The Global Competitiveness Report 2018|publisher=|accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> It ranks first in the world in the [[Economic Complexity Index]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oec.world/en/rankings/country/eci/|title=OEC - Economic Complexity Ranking of Countries (2013-2017)|website=oec.world|language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> Japan is also the world's [[List of largest consumer markets|third-largest consumer market]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NE.CON.PRVT.CD?most_recent_value_desc=true&year_high_desc=true|title=Household final consumption expenditure (current US$) {{!}} Data|website=data.worldbank.org|language=en-us|access-date=7 April 2018}}</ref> \n\nJapan is the world's [[Automotive industry in Japan|third largest automobile manufacturing country]],<ref name=\"2013 PRODUCTION STATISTICS \u2013 FIRST 6 MONTHS\">{{cite web | url=http://www.oica.net/category/production-statistics/ | title=2013 Production Statistics \u2013 First 6 Months | work=[[OICA]] | accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> has the [[Electronics industry in Japan|largest electronics goods industry]], and is often ranked among the world's most innovative countries leading several measures of global [[patent filing]]s.<ref name=\"WIPO Statistics on Patents\">{{cite web | url=http://www.wipo.int/ipstats/en/statistics/patents/ | title=Statistics on Patents | publisher=[[World Intellectual Property Organization]] | date=19 June 2013 | accessdate=16 February 2014}}</ref> Facing increasing competition from China and South Korea,<ref name=\"What does the future hold for Japan's electronics firms?\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-17688322 | title=What does the future hold for Japan's electronics firms? | work=[[BBC News]] | date=12 April 2012 | accessdate=16 October 2013 | author=Morris, Ben}}</ref> [[manufacturing in Japan]] today now focuses primarily on high-tech and precision goods, such as [[optical instrument]]s, [[hybrid vehicle]]s, and [[robotics]]. Besides the [[Kant\u014d region]],<ref name=\"NRI Tokai Industry\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nri.co.jp/english/opinion/papers/2004/pdf/np200475.pdf | title=Strengthening the Competitiveness of Local Industries: The Case of an Industrial Cluster Formed by Three Tokai Prefecters | work=[[Nomura Research Institute]] | date=1 April 2004 | accessdate=16 February 2014 | author=Iwadare, Yoshihiko | page=16}}</ref><ref name=\"Case study of regional university-industry partnership in practice\">{{cite web | url=http://www.iist.or.jp/wf/magazine/0098/0098_E.html | title=Case study of regional university-industry partnership in practice | work=Institute for International Studies and Training | date=1 July 2002 | accessdate=16 February 2014 | author=Kodama, Toshihiro}}</ref><ref name=\"Evaluating the Impacts of Regional Cluster Policies\">{{cite web | url=http://pari.u-tokyo.ac.jp/policy/paper/IAMOT2010_jmori_cluster.pdf | title=Evaluating the Impacts of Regional Cluster Policies using Network Analysis | work=International Association for Management of Technology | year=2010 | accessdate=16 February 2014 |author1=Mori, Junichiro |author2=Kajikawa, Yuya |author3=Sakata, Ichiro | page=9}}</ref><ref name=\"Location and Role of Foreign Firms in Regional Innovation Systems in Japan\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ritsumei.ac.jp/acd/re/k-rsc/ras/04_publications/ria_en/6_01.pdf | title=Location and Role of Foreign Firms in Regional Innovation Systems in Japan | work=[[Ritsumeikan University]] | accessdate=16 February 2014 | author=Schlunze, Rolf D. | page=25}}</ref> the [[Kansai region]] is one of the leading industrial clusters and manufacturing centers for the Japanese economy.<ref name=\"Profile of Osaka/Kansai\">{{cite web | url=http://www.jetro.go.jp/austria/topics/20121112014-topics/Profile.pdf | title=Profile of Osaka/Kansai | work=[[Japan External Trade Organization]] Osaka | accessdate=16 February 2014 | page=10}}</ref> The size and industrial structure of cities in Japan have maintained tight regularities despite substantial churning of population and industries across cities overtime.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1162/adev_a_00096|title = Evolution of the Size and Industrial Structure of Cities in Japan between 1980 and 2010: Constant Churning and Persistent Regularity|journal = Asian Development Review|volume = 34|issue = 2|pages = 86\u2013113|year = 2017|last1 = Mori|first1 = Tomoya}}</ref> Japan is the world's largest [[creditor]] nation.<ref name=\"creditor\">{{cite news|url=http://www.creditwritedowns.com/2011/08/japan-safe-haven.html |work=Credit Writedowns |accessdate=19 June 2013 |title=The yen is a safe haven as Japan is the world's largest creditor |first=Marc |last=Chandler  |date=19 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"creditor 22nd year\">{{cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/japanrealtime/2013/05/28/japan-worlds-largest-creditor-nation-for-22nd-straight-year/ | title=Japan World's Largest Creditor Nation for 22nd Straight Year | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=28 May 2013 | accessdate=14 October 2013 | author=Obe, Mitsuru}}</ref> Japan generally runs an annual trade surplus and has a considerable net international investment surplus. As of 2010, Japan possesses 13.7% of the world's private [[financial asset]]s (the [[List of sovereign states by external assets|third largest in the world]]) at an estimated $13.5 trillion.<ref name=\"fin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allianz.com/v_1443702256000/media/economic_research/publications/specials/en/AGWR2015_ENG.pdf  |work=[[Allianz]] |date=2015 |accessdate=24 March 2016 |title= Allianz Global Wealth Report 2015}}</ref> As of 2017, 51 of the [[Fortune Global 500]] companies are based in Japan,<ref name=\"Global 500 2015\">{{cite web | url=http://fortune.com/global500/ | title=Global 500 (updated) | work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]}}</ref> down from 62 in 2013.<ref name=\"Global 500 2013\">{{cite news | url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/global500/2013/full_list/ | title=Global 500 2013 | work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]}}</ref> The country is the [[List of countries by total wealth|third largest]] in the world by total wealth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.credit-suisse.com/about-us/en/reports-research/global-wealth-report.html|title=Global wealth report|website=Credit Suisse|language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nJapan has the highest ratio of [[National debt of Japan|public debt]] to GDP of any developed nation,<ref name=monstim>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2014/10/31/japan-monetary-stimulus-debt/|title=Japan's latest economic stimulus exposes its dirty debt secret|first=Cyrus|last=Sanati|website=Fortune}}</ref><ref name=timebomb>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2015/02/26/japan-economic-time-bomb/|title=Forget Greece, Japan is the world's real economic time bomb|first=Chris|last=Matthews|website=Fortune}}</ref> with national debt at 236% relative to GDP as of 2017.<ref name=japandebt>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/heres-a-lesson-from-japan-about-the-threat-of-a-us-debt-crisis-2018-05-14/|title=Here's a lesson from Japan about the threat of a U.S. debt crisis |first=Sunny|last=Oh|website=MarketWatch}}</ref> This debt is predominantly owned by Japanese nationals.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterpham/2017/12/11/when-will-japans-debt-crisis-implode/#130f861f4c6d |title = When Will Japan's Debt Crisis Implode?}}</ref> The Japanese economy faces considerable challenges posed by a [[Aging of Japan|declining population]], which peaked at 128 million in 2010 and has fallen to 126.5 million as of 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/SP.POP.TOTL?locations=JP  |work=World Bank |date=2019 |accessdate=12 July 2019 |title= Japan Population}}</ref> Projections suggest the population will continue to fall to potentially lower than 100 million by the middle of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://population.un.org/wpp/Graphs/Probabilistic/POP/TOT/392 |work=United Nations Department of Economic and Social Affairs |date=2015 |accessdate=12 July 2018 |title= World Population Prospects 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/tokyo-gets-more-crowded-as-japan-hollows-out |work=The Straits Times |date=2019 |accessdate=10 July 2019 |title= Tokyo gets more crowded as Japan hollows out 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Overview of the economy==\n<!-- Historical growth of Japan's economy from 1961\u20132015 -->\nIn the three decades of economic development following 1960, rapid economic growth referred to as the [[Japanese post-war economic miracle]] occurred. By the guidance of [[Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry]],<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.unrisd.org/80256B3C005BCCF9/%28httpAuxPages%29/4AD5AF4732C0807FC1256C980035AA30/$file/nakamura.pdf |title= A Declining Technocratic Regime |publisher=United Nations Research Institute for Social Development |first=Toshihiro  |last= Nakamura |journal=Democracy, Governance and Human Rights Programme Paper Number 9 December 2002 |accessdate=20 June 2013 }}</ref> with average growth rates of 10% in the 1960s, 5% in the 1970s, and 4% in the 1980s, Japan was able to establish and maintain itself as the world's second largest economy from 1978 until 2010, when it was surpassed by the [[People's Republic of China]]. By 1990, income per capita in Japan equalled or surpassed that in most countries in the West.<ref>{{cite book|author=Marshall Cavendish Corporation|title=World and Its Peoples: Eastern and Southern Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7M2vqz1Nt0AC&pg=PA1136|year=2007|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-7631-3|page=1136}}</ref>\n\nDuring the second half of the 1980s, rising stock and real estate prices created an [[economic bubble]]. The [[economic bubble]] came to an abrupt end as the [[Tokyo Stock Exchange]] crashed in 1990\u201392 and real estate prices peaked in 1991. Growth in Japan throughout the 1990s at 1.5% was slower than global growth, giving rise to the term [[Lost Decade (Japan)|Lost Decade]]. After another decade of low growth rate, the term became the Lost 20 Years.  Nonetheless, GDP per capita growth from 2001 to 2010 has still managed to outpace Europe and the United States.<ref name=\"gap\">{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21538745 | work=The Economist | title=Whose lost decade? | date=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nWith this low growth rate, the [[national debt of Japan]] has expanded due to its considerable social welfare spending in an aging society with a shrinking tax-base.<ref name=\"monstim\" /><ref name=\"timebomb\" /><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.investasian.com/2014/12/11/fitch-plans-japan-credit-downgrade/ |title=Fitch Plans Japan Credit Downgrade |publisher =InvestAsian|date= |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> The scenario of \"Abandoned homes\" continues to spread from rural areas to urban areas in Japan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2012/05/12/our-lives/can-japans-countryside-be-saved-from-the-edge-of-extinction/#.VfZB0vmSzKB|title=Can Japan's countryside be saved from the edge of extinction? |newspaper =The Japan Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/01/07/national/abandoned-homes-a-growing-menace/ |title=Abandoned homes a growing menace|first=Tomoko|last=Otake|date=7 January 2014|via=Japan Times Online}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2015/05/10/issues/perfect-storm-factors-conspires-empty-japan/#.VfZB5PmSzKA|title=Perfect storm of factors conspires to empty Japan  |newspaper= The Japan Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/79297b7e-24c6-11e5-bd83-71cb60e8f08c.html#axzz3lgHNoRdK|title=Is this the solution to Japan's glut of empty homes?|website=www.ft.com|last = Harding|first = Robin|date = 17 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.tofugu.com/japan/japanese-countryside-emptying/|title=Why the Japanese Countryside Is Emptying|last=Austin |date =6 March 2015|website=Tofugu}}</ref>\n\nA [[mountainous]], volcanic [[island country]], Japan has inadequate [[natural resources]] to support its growing economy and large population, and therefore exports goods in which it has a comparative advantage such as [[engineering]]-oriented, [[research and development]]-led industrial products in exchange for the [[import]] of raw materials and petroleum. Japan is among the top-three importers for agricultural products in the world next to the European Union and United States in total volume for covering of its own domestic agricultural consumption.<ref>http://www.oecd.org/trade/agriculturaltrade/38893266.pdf</ref> Japan is the world's largest single national importer of fish and fishery products.<ref>http://www.fao.org/docrep/013/i1820e/i1820e01.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.fao.org/docrep/016/i2727e/i2727e01.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/fishery/countrysector/naso_japan/en |title=FAO National Aquaculture Sector Overview (NASO) |publisher=Fao.org |date=1 February 2006 |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/fishery/topic/14884/en |title= International trade in aquaculture products |publisher=Fao.org \u2013 FAO Fisheries & Aquaculture|date=1 January 2002 |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref><ref>http://injapan.no/marine/files/2012/03/Miyahara-FA.pdf</ref> [[Tokyo Metropolitan Central Wholesale Market]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shijou.metro.tokyo.jp/info/index.html |title=\u6771\u4eac\u90fd\u4e2d\u592e\u5378\u58f2\u5e02\u5834 &#124; \u5404\u5e02\u5834\u306e\u3054\u7d39\u4ecb |publisher=Shijou.metro.tokyo.jp |date= |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shijou.metro.tokyo.jp/english/structure.html |title=Metropolitan Central Wholesale Market &#124; Structure of The market |publisher=Shijou.metro.tokyo.jp |date= |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> is the largest wholesale market for primary products in Japan, including the renowned Tsukiji fish market.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Murray |first=Maryanne |url=http://www.time.com/time/travel/cityguide/article/0,31489,1897812_1897772_1897703,00.html |title=Tokyo: 10 Things to Do 1. Tsukiji Fish Market |magazine=TIME |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://japandailypress.com/iconic-tsukiji-fish-market-to-close-in-2013-for-new-redesign-1119679 |title=Iconic Tsukiji fish market to close in 2013 for new redesign |publisher=The Japan Daily Press |date= |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> [[Whaling in Japan|Japanese whaling]], ostensibly for research purposes, has been sued as illegal under international law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2018/10/03/japan-kills-endangered-whales-science-sells-meat-thats-illegal-regulator-rules/|title=Japan kills endangered whales for \u2018science\u2019 and sells the meat. That\u2019s illegal, regulator rules.|last=Simon|first=Denyer|date=3 October 2018|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlthough many kinds of minerals were extracted throughout the country, most mineral resources had to be imported in the postwar era. Local deposits of metal-bearing ores were difficult to process because they were low grade. The nation's large and varied forest resources, which covered 70 percent of the country in the late 1980s, were not utilized extensively. Because of political decisions on local, prefectural, and national levels, Japan decided not to exploit its forest resources for economic gain. Domestic sources only supplied between 25 and 30 percent of the nation's timber needs. Agriculture and fishing were the best developed resources, but only through years of painstaking investment and toil. The nation, therefore, built up the manufacturing and processing industries to convert raw materials imported from abroad. This strategy of economic development necessitated the establishment of a strong economic infrastructure to provide the needed energy, transportation, communications, and technological know-how.\n\nDeposits of [[gold]], [[magnesium]], and [[silver]] meet current industrial demands, but Japan is dependent on foreign sources for many of the minerals essential to modern industry. [[Iron ore]], [[copper]], [[bauxite]], and [[alumina]] must be imported, as well as many forest products.\n\nCompared to other industrialized economies, Japan is characterized by its low levels of exports relative to the size of its GDP. From the period 1970-2018, Japan was either the least or second least export-dependent economy in the [[Group of Seven|G7]], and one of the least export-dependent economies in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NE.EXP.GNFS.ZS?locations=US-JP-DE-GB-FR-IT-CA|title=Exports of goods and services (% of GDP) - United States, Japan, Germany, United Kingdom, France, Italy, Canada {{!}} Data|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=2 March 2020}}</ref> It has also been one of the least trade-dependent economies in the 1970-2018 period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NE.TRD.GNFS.ZS?locations=US-JP-DE-GB-FR-IT-CA|title=Trade (% of GDP) - United States, Japan, Germany, United Kingdom, France, Italy, Canada {{!}} Data|website=data.worldbank.org|access-date=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nJapan receives exceptionally low levels of foreign investment. Its inward FDI stock was by far the smallest in the G7 as of 2018, and in fact less than those of much smaller economies such as [[Economy of Austria|Austria]], [[Economy of Poland|Poland]], and [[Economy of Sweden|Sweden]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.oecd.org/chart/5St7|title=Interactive charts by the OECD|website=OECD Data|language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> In fact its ratio of inward FDI stock to GDP is probably the lowest in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.oecd.org/chart/5St9|title=Interactive charts by the OECD|website=OECD Data|language=en|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nJapan lags behind other developed countries in labor productivity. From 1970 to 2018 Japan has consistently had the lowest labor productivity in the G7.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.oecd.org/chart/5StL|title=Interactive charts by the OECD|website=OECD Data|language=en|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Economic history==\n[[File:Hiroshige, Sugura street.jpg|thumb|An 1856 [[ukiyo-e]] depicting Echigoya, the current [[Mitsukoshi]]]]\n{{Main|Economic history of Japan}}\nThe economic history of Japan is one of the most studied.{{verify source|date=March 2020}} First was the foundation of [[Edo]] (in 1603) to whole inland economic developments, second was the [[Meiji Restoration]] (in 1868) to be the first non-European power, third was after the [[surrender of Japan|defeat of World War II]] (in 1945) when the island nation rose to become the world's second largest economy.\n\n===First contacts with Europe (16th century)===\n<!-- PLEASE MAKE CHANGES TO THE MAIN ARTICLES AND THEN UPDATE HERE-->\n{{Main|Nanban trade}}\nJapan was considered as a country rich in precious metals, mainly owing to [[Marco Polo]]'s accounts of gilded temples and palaces, but also due to the relative abundance of surface ores characteristic of a massive huge volcanic country, before large-scale deep-mining became possible in Industrial times.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://web-japan.org/nipponia/nipponia45/en/feature/feature01.html | title=The Legend of \"Zipangu,\" the Land of Gold | work=Nipponia | date=15 June 2008 | accessdate=8 November 2013 | author=Masakatsu, Miyazaki}}</ref> Japan was to become a major exporter of silver, copper, and gold during the period until exports for those minerals were banned.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=nVIPPwVo8eAC&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14&dq=Japan+export+copper+silver#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Intra-Asian Trade in Japanese Copper by the Dutch East India Company During the Eighteenth Century | author=Shimada, Ry\u016bto | year=2006 | page=225| isbn=9004150927 }}</ref>\n\n[[Renaissance]] Japan was also perceived as a sophisticated [[feudal society]] with a high culture and a strong pre-industrial technology. It was densely populated and urbanized. Prominent European observers of the time seemed to agree that the Japanese ''\"excel not only all the other Oriental peoples, they surpass the Europeans as well\"'' ([[Alessandro Valignano]], 1584, \"Historia del Principo y Progresso de la Compania de Jesus en las Indias Orientales).\n\nEarly European visitors were amazed by the quality of Japanese craftsmanship and metalsmithing. This stems from the fact that Japan itself is rather rich in natural resources found commonly in Europe, especially iron.\n\nThe cargo of the first Portuguese ships (usually about 4 smaller-sized ships every year) arriving in Japan almost entirely consisted of Chinese goods (silk, porcelain). The Japanese were very much looking forward to acquiring such goods, but had been prohibited from any contacts with the [[Emperor of China]], as a punishment for [[Wokou|Wak\u014d]] pirate raids. The Portuguese (who were called ''Nanban'', lit. Southern Barbarians) therefore found the opportunity to act as intermediaries in Asian trade.\n\n===Edo period (1603\u20131868)===\n<!-- PLEASE MAKE CHANGES TO THE MAIN ARTICLES AND THEN UPDATE HERE-->\n[[File:\u9d8f\u6587\u9aed\u76bf \u80a5\u524d\u713c\u30fb\u53e4\u4f0a\u4e07\u91cc\u69d8\u5f0f-Barber's Bowl with Cockerel MET DP281043 (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Japanese export porcelain]] in the European shape of a barber's shaving basin bowl, with copulating cock, around 1700.]]\nThe beginning of the [[Edo period]] coincides with the last decades of the [[Nanban trade period]], during which intense interaction with European powers, on the economic and religious plane, took place. It is at the beginning of the Edo period that Japan built her first ocean-going Western-style warships, such as the [[Japanese warship San Juan Bautista|''San Juan Bautista'']], a 500-ton [[galleon]]-type ship that transported a Japanese embassy headed by [[Hasekura Tsunenaga]] to the Americas, which then continued to Europe. Also during that period, the ''bakufu'' commissioned around 350 [[Red Seal Ships]], three-masted and armed trade ships, for intra-Asian commerce. Japanese adventurers, such as [[Yamada Nagamasa]], were active throughout Asia.\n\nIn order to eradicate the influence of [[Christianization]], Japan entered in a period of isolation called [[sakoku]], during which its economy enjoyed stability and mild progress.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Japan/The-bakuhan-system#ref319463|title=The Bakuhan System|last=|first=|date=15 February 2018|website=Encyclopaedia Britannica|access-date=17 February 2018}}</ref>  But not long after, in the 1650s, the production of [[Japanese export porcelain]] increased greatly when civil war put the main Chinese center of porcelain production, [[Jingdezhen porcelain|in Jingdezhen]], out of action for several decades. For the rest of the 17th century, most [[Japanese porcelain]] production was for export, mostly in [[Kyushu]]. The trade dwindled under renewed Chinese competition by the 1740s, before resuming after the opening of Japan in the mid-19th century.<ref>[[David Battie|Battie, David]], ed., ''Sotheby's Concise Encyclopedia of Porcelain'', pp. 71-78, 1990, Conran Octopus. {{ISBN|1850292515}}</ref>     \n\nEconomic development during the Edo period included [[urbanization]], increased shipping of commodities, a significant expansion of domestic and, initially, foreign [[commerce]], and a diffusion of trade and [[handicraft]] industries. The [[construction]] trades flourished, along with banking facilities and [[merchant]] associations. Increasingly, [[Han (country subdivision)|''han'']] authorities oversaw the rising [[agriculture|agricultural]] production and the spread of rural handicrafts.\n\nBy the mid-eighteenth century, Edo had a population of more than 1 million and [[Osaka]] and [[Kyoto]] each had more than 400,000 inhabitants. Many other [[castle town]]s grew as well. Osaka and Kyoto became busy trading and handicraft production centers, while Edo was the center for the supply of food and essential urban consumer goods.\n\nRice was the base of the economy, as the daimy\u014d collected the taxes from the peasants in the form of rice. Taxes were high, about 40% of the harvest. The rice was sold at the ''[[fudasashi]]'' market in [[Edo]]. To raise money, the daimy\u014d used [[forward contract]]s to sell rice that was not even harvested yet. These contracts were similar to modern [[futures trading]].\n\nDuring the period, Japan progressively studied Western sciences and techniques (called ''[[rangaku]]'', literally \"Dutch studies\") through the information and books received through the Dutch traders in [[Dejima]]. The main areas that were studied included geography, medicine, natural sciences, astronomy, art, languages, physical sciences such as the study of electrical phenomena, and mechanical sciences as exemplified by the development of Japanese clockwatches, or [[wadokei]], inspired from Western techniques.\n\n===Pre-war period (1868\u20131945)===\n<!-- PLEASE MAKE CHANGES TO THE MAIN ARTICLES AND THEN UPDATE HERE-->\n\nSince the mid-19th century, after the [[Meiji Restoration]], the country was opened up to Western commerce and influence and Japan has gone through two periods of economic development. The first began in earnest in 1868 and extended through to World War II; the second began in 1945 and continued into the mid-1980s.\n\nEconomic developments of the [[Empire of Japan|prewar period]] began with the \"[[Fukoku ky\u014dhei|Rich State and Strong Army Policy]]\" by the [[Meiji government]]. During the [[Meiji period]] (1868\u20131912), leaders inaugurated a new Western-based education system for all young people, sent thousands of students to the United States and Europe, and hired more than 3,000 Westerners to teach modern science, mathematics, technology, and foreign languages in Japan ([[Oyatoi gaikokujin]]). The government also built railroads, improved road, and inaugurated a land reform program to prepare the country for further development.\n\nTo promote [[industrialization]], the government decided that, while it should help private business to allocate resources and to plan, the public sector was best equipped to stimulate economic growth. The greatest role of government was to help provide good economic conditions for business. In short, government was to be the guide and business the producer. In the early Meiji period, the government built factories and shipyards that were sold to entrepreneurs at a fraction of their value. Many of these businesses grew rapidly into the larger [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerates]]. Government emerged as chief promoter of [[private enterprise]], enacting a series of pro-business policies.\n\nIn the mid-1930s, the Japanese nominal wage rates were \"10 times less\" than the one of the U.S (based on mid-1930s exchange rates), while the price level is estimated to have been about 44% the one of the U.S.<ref>{{cite book |last=Fukao |first=Kyoji |title=Real GDP in Pre-War East Asia: A 1934\u201336 Benchmark Purchasing Power Parity Comparison with the US |year=2007 |url=http://gpih.ucdavis.edu/files/Fukao_Ma_Yuan.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Postwar period (1945\u2013present)===\n[[File:2005Japanese exports.PNG|thumb|right|300px|Japanese exports in 2005]]\n{{See also|Japanese post-war economic miracle|Economic history of Japan}}\n\nFrom the 1960s to the 1980s, overall real economic growth was extremely large: a 10% average in the 1960s, a 5% average in the 1970s and a 4% average in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.country-data.com/cgi-bin/query/r-7176.html | title = Japan: Patterns of Development | publisher = country-data.com |date=January 1994 | accessdate=28 December 2006}}</ref> By the end of said period, Japan had moved into being a high-wage economy.<ref>Business in context: an introduction to business and its environment by David Needle</ref>\n\nGrowth slowed markedly in the late 1990s also termed [[Lost Decade (Japan)|the Lost Decade]] after the collapse of the [[Japanese asset price bubble]]. As a consequence Japan ran massive budget deficits (added trillions in Yen to Japanese financial system) to finance large [[public works]] programs.\n\nBy 1998, Japan's public works projects still could not stimulate demand enough to end the economy's stagnation. In desperation, the Japanese government undertook \"structural reform\" policies intended to wring speculative excesses from the stock and real estate markets. Unfortunately, these policies led Japan into deflation on numerous occasions between 1999 and 2004. The Bank of Japan used [[quantitative easing]] to expand the country's money supply in order to raise expectations of inflation and spur economic growth. Initially, the policy failed to induce any growth, but it eventually began to affect inflationary expectations. By late 2005, the economy finally began what seems to be a sustained recovery. GDP growth for that year was 2.8%, with an annualized fourth quarter expansion of 5.5%, surpassing the growth rates of the US and [[Economy of the European Union|European Union]] during the same period.<ref>Masake, Hisane. [http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Japan/HC02Dh01.html A farewell to zero]. ''Asia Times Online'' (2 March 2006). Retrieved on 28 December 2006.</ref> Unlike previous recovery trends, domestic consumption has been the dominant factor of growth.\n\nDespite having interest rates down near zero for a long period of time, the quantitative easing strategy did not succeed in stopping price deflation.<ref>{{cite news |last=Spiegel |first=Mark |title=Did Quantitative Easing by the Bank of Japan \"Work\"? |date=20 October 2006 |url=http://www.frbsf.org/publications/economics/letter/2006/el2006-28.html}}</ref> This led some economists, such as Paul Krugman, and some Japanese politicians, to advocate the generation of higher inflation expectations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/krugman/www/jpage.html|title=Saving Japan|first=Paul|last=Krugman|website=web.mit.edu}}</ref> In July 2006, the zero-rate policy was ended. In 2008, the Japanese Central Bank still had the lowest interest rates in the developed world, but deflation had still not been eliminated<ref>{{cite news |title=Economic survey of Japan 2008: Bringing an end to deflation under the new monetary policy framework |date=7 April 2008 |url=http://www.oecd.org/document/12/0,3343,en_2649_34115_40363340_1_1_1_1,00.html}}</ref> and the Nikkei 225 has fallen over approximately 50% (between June 2007 and December 2008).  However, on 5 April 2013, the [[Bank of Japan]] announced that it would be purchasing 60\u201370 trillion yen in bonds and securities in an attempt to eliminate deflation by doubling the money supply in Japan over the course of two years.  Markets around the world have responded positively to the government's current proactive policies, with the [[Nikkei 225]] adding more than 42% since November 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/2013/04/04/news/economy/bank-of-japan-decision/index.html | work=CNN | first=Charles | last=Riley | title=Bank of Japan takes fight to deflation | date=4 April 2013}}</ref> [[The Economist]] has suggested that improvements to bankruptcy law, land transfer law, and tax laws will aid Japan's economy. In recent years, Japan has been the top export market for almost 15 trading nations worldwide.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n[[File:JRC N700 series Z28.jpg|thumb|left|200px|[[Shinkansen N700 Series]]]]\n{{Main|Energy in Japan|Transport in Japan}}\n\nIn 2018, Japan ranked 5th overall in the World Bank's [[Logistics Performance Index]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lpi.worldbank.org/international/global|title=Global Rankings 2018 {{!}} Logistics Performance Index|website=lpi.worldbank.org|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> and 2nd in the infrastructure category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lpi.worldbank.org/international/global?sort=asc&order=Infrastructure#datatable|title=Global Rankings 2018 {{!}} Logistics Performance Index|website=lpi.worldbank.org|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, one half of [[energy in Japan|Japan's energy]] was produced from petroleum, a fifth from coal, and 14% from natural gas.<ref>[http://www.stat.go.jp/english/data/handbook/c07cont.htm Chapter 7 Energy] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105175226/http://www.stat.go.jp/english/data/handbook/c07cont.htm |date=5 January 2013 }}, Statistical Handbook of Japan 2007</ref> [[Nuclear power in Japan]] made a quarter of electricity production but due to the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]] there has been a  large desire to end Japan's nuclear power program.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/14/world/asia/14japan.html |title=Japan Premier Wants Shift Away From Nuclear Power |author=Hiroko Tabuchi |date=13 July 2011 |work=The New York Times }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/nn20120103f1.html |title=Fukushima meltdowns set nuclear energy debate on its ear |author=Kazuaki Nagata |date=3 January 2012 |work=The Japan Times }}</ref> In September 2013, Japan closed its last 50 nuclear power plants nationwide, causing the nation to be nuclear free.<ref name=\"Japan goes nuclear-free indefinitely\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/japan-goes-nuclear-free-indefinitely-1.1855153 | title=Japan goes nuclear-free indefinitely | work=[[CBC News]] | date=15 September 2013 | accessdate=9 November 2013}}</ref> The country has since then opted to restart a few of its nuclear reactors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eia.gov/todayinenergy/detail.php?id=38533|title=Nuclear reactor restarts in Japan displacing LNG imports in 2019 - Today in Energy - U.S. Energy Information Administration (EIA)|website=www.eia.gov|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nJapan's spendings on roads has been considered large.<ref name=\"Japan's Road to Deep Deficit Is Paved With Public Works\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/01/world/japan-s-road-to-deep-deficit-is-paved-with-public-works.html | title=Japan's Road to Deep Deficit Is Paved With Public Works | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=1 March 1997 | accessdate=15 November 2013 | author=Pollack, Andrew}}</ref> The 1.2 million kilometers of paved road are one of the major means of transportation.<ref>[http://www.stat.go.jp/english/data/handbook/c09cont.htm Chapter 9 Transport] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427071603/http://www.stat.go.jp/english/data/handbook/c09cont.htm |date=27 April 2011 }}, Statistical Handbook of Japan</ref> Japan has [[Right- and left-hand traffic|left-hand traffic]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.2pass.co.uk/japan.htm#.UoCkUL-lf-m | title=Why Does Japan Drive On The Left? | work=2pass | accessdate=11 November 2013}}</ref> A single network of speed, divided, limited-access toll roads connects major cities and are operated by [[road pricing|toll-collecting enterprises]].<ref>{{cite book | title=All-Japan Road Atlas}}</ref> New and used cars are inexpensive, and the Japanese government has encouraged people to buy [[hybrid vehicle]]s.<ref name=\"Prius No. 1 in Japan sales as green interest grows\">{{cite news | url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/autos/2010-01-08-prius-tops_N.htm | title=Prius No. 1 in Japan sales as green interest grows | work=[[USA Today]] | date=8 January 2013 | accessdate=9 November 2013}}</ref> Car ownership fees and fuel levies are used to promote energy-efficiency.<ref name=\"Prius No. 1 in Japan sales as green interest grows\" />\n\n[[Rail transport in Japan|Rail transport]] is a major means of transport in Japan. [[List of railway companies in Japan|Dozens of Japanese railway companies]] compete in regional and local passenger transportation markets; for instance, 6 passenger [[Japan Railways Group|JR]] enterprises, [[Kintetsu Railway]], [[Seibu Railway]], and [[Keio Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mintetsu.or.jp/activity/databook/pdf/10databook_p02-03.pdf|script-title=ja:\u5927\u624b\u6c11\u9244\u306e\u73fe\u6cc1\uff08\u5358\u4f53\uff09|language=Japanese|author=The Association of Japanese Private Railways|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> Often, strategies of these enterprises contain [[real estate]] or [[Department stores in Japan|department stores next to stations]], and many major stations have major department stores near them.<ref name=\"Osaka dept stores locked in scrap for survival\">{{cite web | url=http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0000769876 | title=Osaka dept stores locked in scrap for survival | publisher=[[Yomiuri Shimbun]] | work=[[Yomiuri Shimbun|The Japan News]] | date=5 November 2013 | accessdate=12 November 2013 |author1=Nagata, Takeshi  |author2=Takahasi, Kentaro}}</ref> The Japanese cities of [[Fukuoka Subway|Fukuoka]], [[Kobe Municipal Subway|Kobe]], [[Kyoto Municipal Transportation Bureau|Kyoto]], [[Nagoya Subway|Nagoya]], [[Osaka Municipal Subway|Osaka]], [[Sapporo Subway|Sapporo]], [[Sendai Subway|Sendai]], [[Tokyo Subway|Tokyo]] and [[Yokohama Subway|Yokohama]] all have [[Rapid transit|subway]] systems. Some 250 high-speed [[Shinkansen]] trains connect major cities.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://jprail.com/travel-informations/tips-for-japan-rail-pass/what-is-shinkansen.html | title=What is Shinkansen (bullet train)? Most convenient and the fastest train service throughout Japan.| work=JPRail.com | date=8 January 2011 | accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> All trains are known for punctuality, and a delay of 90 seconds can be considered late for some train services.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/27/world/asia/27iht-japan.html?_r=0 | title=An obsession with being on time | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=28 April 2005 | accessdate=11 November 2013 | author=Onishi, Norimitsu}}</ref>\n\nThere are 98 passenger and 175 total [[list of airports in Japan|airports in Japan]], and flying is a popular way to travel.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2012/02/07/reference/bubble-eras-aviation-legacy-too-many-airports-all-ailing/#.UoCk8b-lf-n | title=Bubble era's aviation legacy: Too many airports, all ailing | work=[[The Japan Times]] | date=7 February 2013 | accessdate=11 November 2013 | author=Aoki, Mizuho}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldwatch.org/system/files/EWP159.pdf | title=Traveling Light New Paths for International Tourism | work=Worldwatch Paper | date=December 2001 | accessdate=11 November 2013 | author=Mastny, Lisa | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708015751/http://www.worldwatch.org/system/files/EWP159.pdf | archive-date=8 July 2018 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The largest domestic airport, [[Haneda Airport|Tokyo International Airport]], is [[World's busiest airports by passenger traffic|Asia's second busiest airport]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.aci.aero/Data-Centre/Monthly-Traffic-Data/Passenger-Summary/Year-to-date | title=Year to date Passenger Traffic | work=Airports Council International | date=8 November 2013 | accessdate=11 November 2013}}</ref> The largest international gateways are [[Narita International Airport]] (Tokyo area), [[Kansai International Airport]] (Osaka/Kobe/Kyoto area), and [[Ch\u016bbu Centrair International Airport]] (Nagoya area).<ref name=\"Narita airport prepares for battle with Asian hubs\">{{cite web | url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2003/10/25/national/narita-airport-prepares-for-battle-with-asian-hubs/#.UoIMOr-lf-k | title=Narita airport prepares for battle with Asian hubs | work=[[The Japan Times]] | date=25 October 2013 | accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref> The largest ports in Japan include [[Nagoya Port]], the [[Port of Yokohama]], the [[Port of Tokyo]] and the [[Port of Kobe]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.joc.com/sites/default/files/u48783/pdf/Top50-container-2012.pdf | title=The JOC Top 50 World Container Ports | work=[[JOC Group Inc.]] | accessdate=11 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nAbout 84% of Japan's energy is imported from other countries.<ref name=\"Nuclear Power in Japan\">{{cite web | url=http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/Country-Profiles/Countries-G-N/Japan/ | title=Nuclear Power in Japan | work=[[World Nuclear Association]] | date=November 2013 | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Japan's Energy Supply Situation and Basic Policy\">{{cite web | url=http://www.fepc.or.jp/english/energy_electricity/supply_situation/ | title=Japan's Energy Supply Situation and Basic Policy | work=FEPC | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> Japan is the world's largest liquefied natural gas importer, second largest coal importer, and third largest net oil importer.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eia.gov/countries/cab.cfm?fips=JA&trk=p2 | title=Japan | work=[[Energy Information Administration]] | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> Given its heavy dependence on imported energy, Japan has aimed to diversify its sources.<ref name=\"Fukushima Watch: Some Power Companies in Black without Nuclear Restarts\">{{cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/japanrealtime/2013/11/12/fukushima-watch-some-power-companies-in-black-without-nuclear-restarts/ | title=Fukushima Watch: Some Power Companies in Black without Nuclear Restarts | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=12 November 2013 | accessdate=15 November 2013 | author=Iwata, Mari}}</ref> Since the oil shocks of the 1970s, Japan has reduced dependence on petroleum as a source of energy from 77.4% in 1973 to about 43.7% in 2010 and increased dependence on natural gas and nuclear power.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/opinion/2013/11/01/editorials/a-lesson-in-energy-diversification/#.UoXWKb-lf-k | title=A lesson in energy diversification | work=[[The Japan Times]] | date=1 November 2013 | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref>In September 2019, Japan will invest $10 billion on liquefied natural gas projects worldwide, in a strategy to boost the global LNG market and reinforce the security of energy supply.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-japan-lng-conference-meti-idUSKBN1WB050|title=Japan to invest $10 billion in global LNG infrastructure projects: minister|date=26 September 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=26 September 2019|language=en}}</ref> Other important energy source includes coal, and [[Hydroelectricity in Japan|hydroelectricity]] is Japan's biggest renewable energy source.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/10/16/us-japan-power-outlook-idUSBRE99F02A20131016 | title=Japan on gas, coal power building spree to fill nuclear void | work=[[Reuters]] | date=15 October 2013 | accessdate=15 November 2013 |author1=Tsukimori, Osamu |author2=Kebede, Rebekah}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eia.gov/cfapps/ipdbproject/iedindex3.cfm?tid=2&pid=33&aid=12&cid=regions&syid=2005&eyid=2012&unit=BKWH | title=International Energy Statistics | work=[[Energy Information Administration]] | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> Japan's solar market is also currently booming.<ref name=\"Kyocera Boosts Solar Sales Goal on Higher Demand in Japan\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-10-31/kyocera-boosts-solar-sales-goal-on-higher-demand-in-japan.html | title=Kyocera Boosts Solar Sales Goal on Higher Demand in Japan | work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | date=31 October 2013 | accessdate=15 November 2013 | author=Watanabe, Chisaki}}</ref> Kerosene is also used extensively for home heating in portable heaters, especially farther north.<ref name=\"Japan kerosene heater sales surge on power worries\">{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/10/25/idUSL3E7LP15220111025 | title=Japan kerosene heater sales surge on power worries | work=[[Reuters]] | date=25 October 2013 | accessdate=15 November 2013 | author=Maeda, Risa}}</ref> Many taxi companies run their fleets on liquefied natural gas.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ajw.asahi.com/article/economy/business/AJ201307110082 | title=Japan may soon get London-style taxis | work=[[The Asahi Shimbun]] | date=11 July 2013 | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> A recent success towards greater [[Fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] was the introduction of mass-produced [[Hybrid vehicle]]s.<ref name=\"Prius No. 1 in Japan sales as green interest grows\" /> Prime Minister [[Shinz\u014d Abe]], who was working on Japan's economic revival, signed a treaty with [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[UAE]] about the rising prices of oil, ensuring Japan's stable deliveries from that region.<ref name=\"Japan, Saudi Arabia agree on security, energy cooperation\">{{cite web | url=http://ajw.asahi.com/article/behind_news/politics/AJ201305010057 | title=Japan, Saudi Arabia agree on security, energy cooperation | work=[[The Asahi Shimbun]] | date=1 May 2013 | accessdate=15 November 2013 | author=Suzuki, Takuya}}</ref><ref name=\"Abe clinches nuclear technology deal with Abu Dhabi\">{{cite web | url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/05/03/national/abe-clinches-nuclear-technology-deal-with-abu-dhabi/#.UoX_Xr-lf-k | title=Abe clinches nuclear technology deal with Abu Dhabi | work=[[The Japan Times]] | date=3 May 2013 | accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Macro-economic trend ==\n[[File:Real GDP growth rate in Japan (1956-2008).png|250px|thumb|Real GDP growth rate from 1956 to 2008]]\n[[File:Okun's law Japan.svg|thumb|250px|Quarterly change in the real GDP (blue) and the unemployment rate (red) of Japan from 2000 to 2010. See [[Okun's law]].]]\nThis is a chart of trend of gross domestic product of Japan at market prices estimated by the [[International Monetary Fund]] with figures in millions of Japanese Yen.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2010/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?sy=2008&ey=2015&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=158&s=NGDP%2CNGDPD%2CPCPIE&grp=0&a=&pr1.x=41&pr1.y=8 | title=Report for Selected Countries and Subjects | accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref> See also<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stat.go.jp/english/data/chouki/03.htm|title=Statistics Bureau Home Page/Chapter 3 National Accounts|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.measuringworth.org/datasets/japandata|title=Measuring Worth - Japan|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n| '''Year''' || '''Gross domestic product''' || '''US dollar exchange''' || '''Price index<br />(2000=100)''' || '''Nominal per-capita GDP<br />(as % of US)'''|| '''PPP capita GDP<br />(as % of US)'''\n|-\n| 1955 || 8,369,500 || \uffe5360.00 || || 10.31 || \u2013\n|-\n| 1960 || 16,009,700 