| .294 || .811 || 2.9 ||\t1.6 ||\t.4 ||\t.3 ||\t6.2\n|-\n| align=left | {{pbay|2013}}\n| align=left | Alaska\n| 44 ||\t21.8 || .342 || .358 || .596 || 3.0 ||\t1.1 ||\t.5 ||\t.1 ||\t6.2\n|-\n| align=left | {{pbay|2014}}\n| align=left | Alaska\n| 57 ||\t21.3 || .359 || .343 || .758 || 2.5 ||\t1.2 ||\t.5 ||\t.2 ||\t7.6\n|-\n| align=left | {{pbay|2015}}\n| align=left | Alaska\n| 57 ||\t15.2 || .376 || .338 || '''.837''' || 1.5 ||\t.9 ||\t.4 ||\t.1 ||\t5.7\n|-\n| align=left | {{pbay|2016}}\n| align=left | Alaska\n| 21 ||\t11.5 || .317 || .321 || .500 || 1.4 ||\t.8 ||\t.1 ||\t.0 || 3.5\n|-class=sortbottom\n| align=center colspan=2 | Career\n| 744 || 26.1 || .378 || .336 || .704 || 3.4 ||\t1.8 ||\t.6 ||\t.3 || 9.8\n{{end}}\n\n==International career==\nHontiveros played for the Philippine National Team in 2002 and 2007. He also donned the national colors for the Smart-Gilas Team Pilipinas in 2011 and helped Gilas Pilipinas defeat Japan in the semifinals of the 2015 FIBA Asia Championship in China.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Belen |first1=Reynaldo |title=Hontiveros bows out of SMART-Gilas; new Talk \u2018N Text player likely to take spot |url=http://www.interaksyon.com/interaktv/hontiveros-bows-out-of-smart-gilas-new-talk-n-text-player-likely-to-take-spot |work=InterAksyon.com |date=August 19, 2011 |accessdate=January 21, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121074330/http://www.interaksyon.com/interaktv/hontiveros-bows-out-of-smart-gilas-new-talk-n-text-player-likely-to-take-spot |archive-date=January 21, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHontiveros is a [[Christians|Christian]], and has a son named Isaiah with singer and fellow Cebu native Gail Blanco. He speaks three languages - his native [[Cebuano Language|Cebuano]], [[English language|English]] and [[Tagalog Language|Tagalog]]. He is also a cousin to Philippine Senator [[Risa Hontiveros|Risa]] and [[CNN Philippines]] anchor [[Pia Hontiveros]].\n\nHe has also worn the following numbers during his career: the numbers 7 with Cebu Gems and San Miguel, the number 34 which was his first jersey number with Tanduay, and 24 with Air21, and 25 with Alaska Aces.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{navboxes colour\n|title=Philippines squad\n|bg= #0038A8\n|fg= White\n|list1=\n {{Philippines Squad 2007 William Jones Cup}}\n {{Philippines Squad 2007 FIBA Asia Championship}}\n {{Philippines squad 2015 William Jones Cup}}\n {{Philippines Squad FIBA Asia Championship 2015}}\n}}\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{San Miguel Beermen 2005 PBA Fiesta Conference Champions}}\n{{San Miguel Beermen 2009 PBA Fiesta Conference Champions}}\n{{Alaska Aces 2013 PBA Commissioner's Cup Champions}}\n{{PBA Sportsmanship Awardees}}\n}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hontiveros, Dondon}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alaska Aces (PBA) players]]\n[[Category:Barako Bull Energy players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2002 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Cebu]]\n[[Category:Cebuano people]]\n[[Category:Filipino sportsperson-politicians]]\n[[Category:Philippine Basketball Association All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Philippine Basketball Association broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Philippines men's national basketball team players]]\n[[Category:Filipino men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:San Miguel Beermen players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Cebu City]]\n[[Category:San Miguel Alab Pilipinas players]]\n[[Category:Tanduay Rhum Masters players]]\n[[Category:Asian Games competitors for the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "112.206.200.65", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSeason-by-season averages)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dondon_Hontiveros"}
{"title_page": "Everyone Poops", "text_new": "{{short description|1993 book by Tar\u014d Gomi}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Everyone Poops\n| title_orig    = Minna Unchi<br>(\u307f\u3093\u306a\u3046\u3093\u3061)\n| translator    = Amanda Mayer Stinchecum\n| image         = Everyone Poops.jpg\n| caption = Hardcover English 1st ed.\n| author        = [[Tar\u014d Gomi]]\n| illustrator   = Tar\u014d Gomi\n| cover_artist  = Tar\u014d Gomi\n| country       = [[Japan]]\n| language      = [[Japanese language|Japanese]]\n| series        = Kagaku no Tomo Kessaku-sh\u016b in Japan,<br>\nMy Body Science in the USA\n| genre         = [[Children's non-fiction literature]]\n| publisher     = [[Kane/Miller]] (Eng. trans)\n| release_date  = January 17, 1977\n| english_release_date = March 1, 1993\n| media_type    = Print ([[Hardcover]] & [[Paperback]])\n| pages         = 27 pp<ref name=\"bnn\">{{cite book |author=Taro Gomi |translator=Amanda Mayer Stinchecum |title=Girls poop too |date=1993 |publisher=Kane/Miller Book Publishers |location=Brooklyn, N.Y. |isbn=978-0-916291-45-7 |edition=1st American |url=https://archive.org/details/everyonepoops00gomi }}</ref>\n| isbn = 978-0-916291-45-7\n| isbn_note = (first American edition, hardcover)\n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\n'''''Everyone Poops''''' is the title of US editions of the English translation (by Amanda Mayer Stinchecum) of {{Nihongo|'''''Minna Unchi'''''|\u307f\u3093\u306a\u3046\u3093\u3061|}}, a [[Japanese language|Japanese]] [[children's literature|children's book]] written and illustrated by the prolific children's author [[Tar\u014d Gomi]] and first published in [[Japan]] by [[Fukuinkan Shoten]] in 1977 within the series {{nihongo|''Kagaku no Tomo Kessaku-sh\u016b''|\u304b\u304c\u304f\u306e\u3068\u3082\u5091\u4f5c\u96c6||i.e. Masterpieces of the friends of science}}.\n\nThe English translation has been published in the US by [[Kane/Miller]], within the series \"My Body Science\", and by [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]]. In Britain, the book is titled '''''Everybody Poos''''' and is published by [[Frances Lincoln]].\n\nThe book tells children that all animals [[Defecation|defecate]] and that they have always done so.\n\nThe book has also been translated into Spanish and [[Thai language|Thai]].\n\n==Story==\n''Everyone Poops'' does not have a plot. The first sixteen pages contain various prompts regarding defecation in animals such as opposites (\"An elephant makes a big poop\" and \"[a] mouse makes a tiny poop\"), comparisons (that various species produce various sizes and shapes of poop) and questions (\"What does whale poop look like?\").<ref name=\"start\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | pp=1\u201316 | Ref=none}}</ref><ref name=\"go\">{{cite web|title=Book Review: Everyone Poops|url=http://family.go.com/entertainment/article-csm-117740-book-review--everyone-poops-t/|accessdate=2009-02-15|last=Gennari|first=Jennifer|publisher=[[Disney]] Family Entertainment}}</ref>\n\nOn the seventeenth page, a nameless boy with black [[overalls]] and a red shirt is introduced, seen running into a bathroom. The book then goes on to explain how people of all ages, from adult to very young child, defecate, and how [[infants]] may use [[diapers]].<ref name=\"go\" /><ref name=\"eini\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | pp=18\u201319 | Ref=none}}</ref> After that, there are only three more illustrations that do not feature the boy.<ref name=\"noboy\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | pp=20\u201322 | Ref=none}}</ref> On the next page of the book, the child uses [[toilet paper]] and flushes the toilet.<ref name=\"sing\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | p=23 | Ref=none}}</ref><ref name=\"chi\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | p=18 | Ref=none}}</ref> The final portion of the book explains that because every animal eats, they must therefore defecate, and the book ends with rear views of the boy and six different animals defecating and the words \"Everyone Poops\".<ref name=\"endo\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | pp=24\u201327 | Ref=none}}</ref><ref name=\"ehon\">{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u300c\u307f\u3093\u306a\u3046\u3093\u3061\u300d|url=http://www.ehonnavi.net/ehon00.asp?no=178|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-02-16|publisher=EhonNavi|year=2009}}</ref>\n\n==Publication==\n''Everyone Poops'' was written by [[Tar\u014d Gomi]], and first published by [[Tokyo]]-based [[Fukuinkan Shoten]] as ''Minna Unchi'' in 1977.<ref name=\"fuku\">{{cite web|title=About Fukuinkan Shoten|url=http://www.fukuinkan.com/aboutus.html|year=2008|publisher=Fukuinkan Shoten|accessdate=2009-02-20}}</ref>\n\nIt was acquired by Kane/Miller in 1993.  Kane/Miller was later bought by Educational Development Corporation. ''Everyone Poops'' is the best-known title sold by the company.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.tulsaworld.com/businesshomepage1/educational-development-corporation-succeeds-despite-amazon/article_d043fe32-d088-584c-98af-9479db33c420.html|title = Educational Development Corporation succeeds despite Amazon|last = Evatt|first = Robert|date = 21 June 2014|work = Tulsa World|accessdate = }}\n</ref> This book is sold in the U.S. through traditional bookstores such as [[Barnes & Noble]] and on the [[party plan]] by independent booksellers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Editions==\n*{{in lang|ja}} ''Minna Unchi'' ({{nihongo2|\u307f\u3093\u306a\u3046\u3093\u3061}}). Kagaku no Tomo Kessaku-sh\u016b ({{nihongo2|\u304b\u304c\u304f\u306e\u3068\u3082\u5091\u4f5c\u96c6}}). Tokyo: Fukuinkan Shoten ({{nihongo2|\u798f\u97f3\u9928\u66f8\u5e97}}), 1977. For later printings, {{ISBN|4-8340-0848-7}}. 28 pages in Japanese edition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fukuinkan.co.jp/bookdetail.php?isbn=978-4-8340-0848-7 |script-title=ja:\u798f\u97f3\u9928\u66f8\u5e97\uff5c\u307f\u3093\u306a\u3046\u3093\u3061 |language=ja |publisher=Fukuinkan.co.jp |accessdate=2013-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325091317/http://www.fukuinkan.co.jp/bookdetail.php?isbn=978-4-8340-0848-7 |archive-date=2012-03-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''Everyone Poops.'' Trans. Amanda Mayer Stinchecum. My Body Science. Brooklyn, N.Y.: Kane/Miller, 1993. {{ISBN|0-916291-45-6}}.\n* ''Everyone Poops.'' Trans. Amanda Mayer Stinchecum. La Jolla: Kane/Miller, 2001. {{ISBN|1-929132-14-X}}. New York: Scholastic, 2004. {{ISBN|0-439-72659-X}}.\n* ''Everybody Poos.'' Trans. Amanda Mayer Stinchecum. London: Frances Lincoln, 2002. {{ISBN|0-7112-2046-8}}. London: Frances Lincoln, 2004. {{ISBN|1-84507-258-8}}\n*{{in lang|es}} ''Todos hacemos caca.'' Trans: Leopoldo Iribarren. Brooklyn, N.Y.: Kane/Miller, 1997. {{ISBN|0-916291-77-4}}\n*{{in lang|th}} ''\u02bb\u01af.'' Krung Th\u0113p: Samnakphim Phr\u01e3o Ph\u01b0\u0304an Dek, 1995. {{ISBN|974-89200-0-3}}. Krungth\u0113p: \u02bbAmmarin, 2003. {{ISBN|974-247-036-7}}.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Japan|Children's literature}}\n*[[Toilet training]]\n*''[[The Gas We Pass]]''\n*''[[What's Your Poo Telling You?]]''\n*''[[The Story of the Little Mole Who Knew It Was None of His Business]]''\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:1977 children's books]]\n[[Category:Japanese books]]\n[[Category:Japanese picture books]]\n[[Category:Books about feces]]\n[[Category:Books about toilet training]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1993 book by Tar\u014d Gomi}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Everyone Poops\n| title_orig    = Minna Unchi<br>(\u307f\u3093\u306a\u3046\u3093\u3061)\n| translator    = Amanda Mayer Stinchecum\n| image         = Everyone Poops.jpg\n| caption = Hardcover English 1st ed.\n| author        = [[Tar\u014d Gomi]]\n| illustrator   = Tar\u014d Gomi\n| cover_artist  = Tar\u014d Gomi\n| country       = [[Japan]]\n| language      = [[Japanese language|Japanese]]\n| series        = Kagaku no Tomo Kessaku-sh\u016b in Japan,<br>\nMy Body Science in the USA\n| genre         = [[Children's non-fiction literature]]\n| publisher     = [[Kane/Miller]] (Eng. trans)\n| release_date  = January 17, 1977\n| english_release_date = March 1, 1993\n| media_type    = Print ([[Hardcover]] & [[Paperback]])\n| pages         = 27 pp<ref name=\"bnn\">{{cite book |author=Taro Gomi |translator=Amanda Mayer Stinchecum |title=Everyone poops |date=1993 |publisher=Kane/Miller Book Publishers |location=Brooklyn, N.Y. |isbn=978-0-916291-45-7 |edition=1st American |url=https://archive.org/details/everyonepoops00gomi }}</ref>\n| isbn = 978-0-916291-45-7\n| isbn_note = (first American edition, hardcover)\n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   = \n}}\n\n'''''Everyone Poops''''' is the title of US editions of the English translation (by Amanda Mayer Stinchecum) of {{Nihongo|'''''Minna Unchi'''''|\u307f\u3093\u306a\u3046\u3093\u3061|}}, a [[Japanese language|Japanese]] [[children's literature|children's book]] written and illustrated by the prolific children's author [[Tar\u014d Gomi]] and first published in [[Japan]] by [[Fukuinkan Shoten]] in 1977 within the series {{nihongo|''Kagaku no Tomo Kessaku-sh\u016b''|\u304b\u304c\u304f\u306e\u3068\u3082\u5091\u4f5c\u96c6||i.e. Masterpieces of the friends of science}}.\n\nThe English translation has been published in the US by [[Kane/Miller]], within the series \"My Body Science\", and by [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]]. In Britain, the book is titled '''''Everybody Poos''''' and is published by [[Frances Lincoln]].\n\nThe book tells children that all animals [[Defecation|defecate]] and that they have always done so.\n\nThe book has also been translated into Spanish and [[Thai language|Thai]].\n\n==Story==\n''Everyone Poops'' does not have a plot. The first sixteen pages contain various prompts regarding defecation in animals such as opposites (\"An elephant makes a big poop\" and \"[a] mouse makes a tiny poop\"), comparisons (that various species produce various sizes and shapes of poop) and questions (\"What does whale poop look like?\").<ref name=\"start\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | pp=1\u201316 | Ref=none}}</ref><ref name=\"go\">{{cite web|title=Book Review: Everyone Poops|url=http://family.go.com/entertainment/article-csm-117740-book-review--everyone-poops-t/|accessdate=2009-02-15|last=Gennari|first=Jennifer|publisher=[[Disney]] Family Entertainment}}</ref>\n\nOn the seventeenth page, a nameless boy with black [[overalls]] and a red shirt is introduced, seen running into a bathroom. The book then goes on to explain how people of all ages, from adult to very young child, defecate, and how [[infants]] may use [[diapers]].<ref name=\"go\" /><ref name=\"eini\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | pp=18\u201319 | Ref=none}}</ref> After that, there are only three more illustrations that do not feature the boy.<ref name=\"noboy\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | pp=20\u201322 | Ref=none}}</ref> On the next page of the book, the child uses [[toilet paper]] and flushes the toilet.<ref name=\"sing\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | p=23 | Ref=none}}</ref><ref name=\"chi\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | p=18 | Ref=none}}</ref> The final portion of the book explains that because every animal eats, they must therefore defecate, and the book ends with rear views of the boy and six different animals defecating and the words \"Everyone Poops\".<ref name=\"endo\">{{Harvnb | Gomi | 1993 | pp=24\u201327 | Ref=none}}</ref><ref name=\"ehon\">{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u300c\u307f\u3093\u306a\u3046\u3093\u3061\u300d|url=http://www.ehonnavi.net/ehon00.asp?no=178|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-02-16|publisher=EhonNavi|year=2009}}</ref>\n\n==Publication==\n''Everyone Poops'' was written by [[Tar\u014d Gomi]], and first published by [[Tokyo]]-based [[Fukuinkan Shoten]] as ''Minna Unchi'' in 1977.<ref name=\"fuku\">{{cite web|title=About Fukuinkan Shoten|url=http://www.fukuinkan.com/aboutus.html|year=2008|publisher=Fukuinkan Shoten|accessdate=2009-02-20}}</ref>\n\nIt was acquired by Kane/Miller in 1993.  Kane/Miller was later bought by Educational Development Corporation. ''Everyone Poops'' is the best-known title sold by the company.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|